  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus contains detailed discussions of child-rearing primarily in the ancient Indic Dharmaśāstra texts (Smṛtis), which prescribe rituals (*saṃskāras*), moral training, education, and varṇa-specific duties from conception through youth. These are framed as religious and social obligations rather than modern parenting advice. No works provide comprehensive guides solely on child psychology or daily discipline, but the following offer explicit rules:**\n\n- **Manusmṛti** (by Manu): Chapter 2 extensively details the upbringing of male children (especially *twice-born* Brahminas, Kshatriyas, and Vaiśyas), including birth rites, naming on the 10th/12th day,[^1] first feeding at 6 months, tonsure at 1-3 years, initiation (*upanayana*) at ages 8/11/12 (or up to 16/22/24),[^2] wearing deerskin/girdle/staff/sacred thread by varṇa, begging alms, serving the *guru*, sense control, daily *Sāvitrī* recitation, sleeping on the ground, avoiding women/perfumes/meat, and prohibitions like spilling seed.[^3] Girls receive similar rites without mantras, with marriage as their \"Vedic *saṃskāra*.\"[^4] This chapter outlines the *brahmacarya* (student) phase as ideal rearing for virtue.[^5]\n\nOther Smṛtis (e.g., **Yājñavalkya Smṛti**, **Pārāśara Smṛti**, **Viṣṇu Smṛti**, **Kātyāyana Smṛti**) likely cover similar topics across their chapters on *ācāra* (conduct) and *āśrama* (life stages), as they follow Manu's model, but I found no uniquely explicit sections beyond general varṇa duties.\n\n**French liberal works mention child education incidentally:**\n- **Traité de la propriété (Vol. I)** by Charles Comte notes permanent family unions for \"the education of children\" as natural across societies.[^6]\n- **Traité de Législation (Vol. I)** by Charles Comte links savings to affording children's education.[^7]\n- **Nouveau traité d'économie (Vol. I)** by Charles Dunoyer references \"physical education of children\" improving health/population.[^8]\n\n**No explicit discussions appear in poetry (e.g., Cynewulf, Iqbal, Ghalib), Kawi texts, or other listed works. If absent from searches/chapters sampled, topics like modern child psychology are not covered.** \n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-56acee).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-64fab3).\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-c97d34).\n[^4]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-ee075b).\n[^5]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/).\n[^6]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété*, [Ch. 7](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/07-du-territoire-propre-a-chaque-nation/translation/#p-b57864).\n[^7]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation*, [Vol. I, Ch. 18](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/18-des-elements-de-puissance-dont-se-composent-les-lo/translation/#p-a19da8).\n[^8]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie*, [Vol. I, Ch. 5](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/05-liberte-compatible-avec-la-maniere-de-vivre-des-pe/translation/#p-3bb243).",
